The Fanatics of Free Trade
From Cambridge —— Recently, I was invited to guest lecture in a globalization course taught by two of my Harvard colleagues. "I must warn you."
One of them warned me in advance: "These students are strong advocates of globalization."
He had asked the students in the first class to choose between free trade and import restrictions, and over 90% favored the former.
And this was before he had even begun to teach the magical effects of comparative advantage.
We know that in real surveys, asking the same question to representative samples — rather than Harvard students — would yield a completely different result.
In the United States, the ratio of opponents to supporters of trade restrictions is 2:1.
But Harvard students' answers would not be particularly surprising.
Because those with higher technical skills and better education tend to be more in favor of free trade than blue-collar workers.
And perhaps these Harvard students have already anticipated their future (financial) prospects and made their decisions accordingly.
Or perhaps, they actually don't understand how trade works.
After all, when I met with them, I特意 changed the way I asked the same question and emphasized the distributional effects that trade might generate.
The consensus in favor of fair trade completely disappeared, even more quickly than I had anticipated.
At the beginning, I first asked everyone whether they agreed to participate in a particularly magical experiment.
I selected Nicholas and John as volunteers, and then told them that I had a way to make 200 dollars disappear from Nicholas's account —— poof! —— while simultaneously adding 300 dollars to John's account, a feat of social engineering that could add an additional 100 dollars in value to the entire class.
Would they allow me to perform this little trick?
Only a small portion firmly agreed, many were hesitant, and even more opposed the implementation of this change.

Clearly, the students found it difficult to tolerate such a form of massive redistribution of income, even when the overall economic cake had been made bigger.
I then asked why the majority of them almost instinctively supported free trade, which actually leads to a similar —— in fact, even more significant —— redistribution of wealth from losers to winners.
The students looked stunned.
I then said, let's assume that Nicholas and John each run a competing small company.
John works harder, saves and invests more, and produces better products, so he not only ends up with $300 more than Nicholas but also drives Nicholas's company out of the market, causing Nicholas to lose $200.
How many students would then support this change?
This time, the majority voted in favor — in fact, only Nicholas himself disagreed!
I then immediately proposed another hypothesis directly related to international trade.
If John drove Nicholas out of the market by importing high-quality products from Germany?
Or by outsourcing business processes to China, where labor rights are not yet fully established?
Or by hiring child labor in Indonesia?
This time, the level of support for the change decreased sequentially with the above options.
Moreover, technological innovation can also, like trade, leave certain groups in a more disadvantaged position. What is your view on this?
Only a very few students were willing to restrain technological development.
To almost everyone, banning the production of light bulbs in order to protect the jobs of candle makers is a ridiculous idea.
Therefore, what the students oppose is not redistribution per se, but rather certain specific forms of redistribution.
Like most of us, they care about the fairness of the process.
If we are to judge the results of redistribution, we must know the objective context that produced such results.
We would not be resentful of Bill Gates or Warren Buffett's enormous wealth, even if some of their competitors have always had a hard time, probably because they and their competitors all operate according to the same basic laws and face very similar opportunities and challenges.
But if Gates and Buffett had become wealthy not through their own intelligence and effort, but through fraud, violation of labor laws, environmental destruction, or by exploiting subsidies from foreign governments, our views would be completely different.
If we cannot tolerate redistribution achieved through violations of widely accepted moral standards within our country, how can we feel at ease with redistribution that involves cross-border transactions?
Similarly, when we expect the redistributive effects to equalize in the long run, and everyone will ultimately benefit from it, we are likely to pay no attention to the transfer of income.
This is also why we believe that despite the short-term negative effects technology may have on some people, we are still willing to promote its development.
On the other hand, when trade continuously impacts the same group of people — low-educated blue-collar workers — we become worried about globalization.
But many economists ignore these obvious differences.
They tend to attribute concerns about globalization to foolish and selfish protectionist motives or ignorance, without realizing that the most important issue is actually a moral one.
Because they fail to recognize that international trade — although not often — sometimes leads to redistribution consequences that we would not accept domestically, these economists are also unable to properly engage in public discourse.
And if they are not even morally defensible, how can they vigorously defend trade?
When globalization occasionally raises a thorny issue related to the legitimization of redistribution effects, we should not respond with trade restrictions without thinking.
There are still many pros and cons to be carefully weighed, including the possibility that globalization may cause more severe wealth deprivation for people in other places than for victims in the United States itself.
However, democratic countries should have a more appropriate discussion on this and make more conscious and thoughtful decisions.
And that kind of infatuation with globalization simply because it has made the cake bigger will ultimately erode the legitimacy of globalization itself in the long run.
